<?xml version="1.0"?>
<!--
  Mesh-based Orion URDF. Uses the AROW-derived orion.glb vendored at
  models/orion.glb (originally from github.com/iandees/artemis-viewer,
  re-published from NASA's "Track NASA's Artemis II in Real Time" page,
  AROW). Same spacecraft model NASA's official live tracker shows: detailed
  CM, SM, engine bell, RCS thrusters, antennae, hardware, AND the four solar
  arrays (SAW1..SAW4) deployed in their on-orbit configuration.

  AROW authored the four arrays folded against the hull with no deployable
  hinge metadata exposed in the glb. Ian Dees worked out per-array
  position+rotation overrides interactively in his Three.js viewer's
  panel-tuning tool; we apply those same per-node transforms at build
  time (see _AROW_PANEL_TRANSFORMS in scripts/build_mcap.py) so the
  AROW arrays render in their correct deployed pose. The result is a
  fully detailed body + factory-correct deployed wings, with no synthetic
  primitive geometry.

  Body scale: 7,000,000x. AROW's glb is normalized to a unit cube (native
  AABB ~0.88 x 0.85 x 1.0; longest axis = 1.0), so `<mesh scale>` here is
  in "metres of final body extent" rather than "real-world meters of the
  spacecraft". At 7,000,000 the body is about Earth-radius in extent
  (6.4 Mm), big enough to read at our default 30,000 km camera distance.

  Body axes: AROW's glb is Y-up (CM at glb +Y, SM at -Y); the layout's
  meshUpAxis "y_up" tells the 3D panel to convert to Z-up by rotating 90°
  around X. After that rotation: glb +Y becomes URDF +Z (CM at top), glb
  +X stays URDF +X, and glb +Z becomes URDF -Y. The deployed SAWs end up
  spread roughly along URDF +X/-X/+Y/-Y around the SM mid-section.

  Build step: `scripts/build_mcap.py` reads models/orion.glb, applies the
  per-SAW deployment transforms, and substitutes the mesh filename below
  with a base64 `data:model/gltf-binary;base64,...` payload. The MCAP is
  then fully self-contained and Foxglove does not fetch anything at runtime.
  A processed copy is also written to data/cache/orion-deployed.glb for
  inspection.

  To skip SAW deployment (arrays stay folded against the hull): pass the
  no_deploy_panels flag to scripts/build_mcap.py. To skip the mesh entirely:
  build with urdf=models/orion-primitives.urdf.

  XML caveat: avoid the literal "double hyphen" sequence anywhere in
  this comment block. XML 1.0 forbids it inside an XML comment and the
  URDF parser silently rejects the file with "No robot found in URDF".

  Attribution: NASA's AROW assets are covered by the NASA Images and
  Media Usage Guidelines (effectively public-domain for non-commercial
  use; see www.nasa.gov/nasa-brand-center/images-and-media/). The glb
  itself was extracted from AROW's Unity bundle and re-hosted by Ian Dees
  at iandees/artemis-viewer; the per-SAW deployment transforms in
  `_AROW_PANEL_TRANSFORMS` were also tuned by him.
-->
<robot name="orion">
  <link name="orion">
    <!-- AROW spacecraft body + SAW1..SAW4 deployed. -->
    <visual>
      <origin xyz="0 0 0" rpy="0 0 0"/>
      <geometry>
        <mesh filename="orion.glb"
              scale="7000000 7000000 7000000"/>
      </geometry>
    </visual>
  </link>
</robot>
